{{Infobox political party | name = Marijuana Reform Party | logo = Marijuana Reform Party logo.jpg | colorcode = Green | leader = | spokesperson = | foundation = 1997 | ideology = [[Removal of cannabis from Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act|Cannabis legalization]] | headquarters = | international = | website = | country = United States | chair = | abbreviation = MRP | dissolved = 2004 }}
The '''Marijuana Reform Party''' (abbreviated '''MRP''')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/onpolitics/elections/2001/results/parties.htm|title=Key to Party Abbreviations|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|year=2001|accessdate=November 13, 2009}}</ref> was a [[progressivism|progressive]] [[List of political parties in the United States#Categorizing U.S. political parties|minor]] [[political party]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]] dedicated to the [[Cannabis rescheduling in the United States|legalization]] of [[cannabis]].<ref name=Siegel>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1998/05/26/1998-05-26_pol_is_taking_a_pot_shot__go.html|title=Pol is taking a pot show gov wanna-be has inhaled|first=Joel|last=Siegel|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|date=May 26, 1998|accessdate=November 13, 2009}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Founded in 1997, the Marijuana Reform Party ran a candidate for [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]] and other statewide offices in 1998 and 2002.<ref name=Burnt>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/article-10743-burnt-out.html|title=Burnt Out|date=December 28, 2004|accessdate=November 13, 2009|work=[[New York Press]]|publisher=[[Manhattan Media]]}} Note: Text may be scrambled, but can be copied.</ref>
Finding that the ability of the Marijuana Reform Party to submit [[petition]]s containing enough signatures to run candidates in statewide elections demonstrated that it enjoyed a modicum of support in the New York State electorate, in 2004 a [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|federal appeals court]] ordered the New York state board of elections to recognize the Marijuana Reform Party, allow voters to enroll in it, and to tabulate and make available lists of voters enrolled in the party.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}
The Marijuana Reform Party was one of several minor parties that fulfilled a role almost unique to New York State politics. New York law allows [[electoral fusion]] &mdash; a candidate can be the nominee of multiple parties and aggregate the votes received on all the different ballot lines. Several other states allow fusion, but only in New York is it commonly practiced. In fact, since each party is listed with its own line on New York ballots, multiple nominations mean that a candidate's name can be listed several times on the ballot.
